abstract.para: The study consists of 16 treatment units â stands ranging in size from 7 to 11 ha â within the H.J. Andrews Experimental Forest. Each unit is has assigned one of four alternative thinning regimes â unthinned (Control), light thin with patch openings (GAP), light thin (Light) or heavy thin (Heavy),. The stands are to be managed under these alternative regimes over several harvest cycles as the experiment evaluates alternative thinning regimes to convert uniform, even-aged stands, to structurally heterogeneous uneven-aged structure. Vegetation data collection occurred pretreatment (1997 or 1998) and post-treatment (2001, 2003, 2005 and 2010).

additionalInfo.para: As a collaborative effort, implementation and data collection are performed by McKenzie River Ranger District personnel. The Pacific Northwest Research Station provides study oversight, data analysis and reporting.

intellectualRights.para: Welcome to the H. J. Andrews LTER Database. Our intentions are to make our data as freely available as possible (See http://andrewsforest.oregonstate.edu/data/policy#DATAREL). Our data sets consist of long-term research study data with accompanying documentation (metadata). Spatial and non-spatial data sets are available as well as software and models. We encourage the use of our data sets, but as a professional courtesy we ask that data users read and agree to the terms of our Use Agreement (http://andrewsforest.oregonstate.edu/data/policy#DATAUSE). It is considered a matter of professional ethics to acknowledge the work of other scientists that results in data used in subsequent research. Therefore, Andrews Forest researchers request appropriate citation and acknowledgement for subsequent distribution or publication of any work derived from these data sets. Data users are strongly encouraged to consider consultation, collaboration and/or co-authorship with original investigators.
Acknowledgement of the USFS Pacific Northwest Research Station and the Willamette National Forest.

description.para: Experimental treatment units with a minimum of 20 ac (8 ha) were harvested according to treatment assignment using an operational Forest Service harvest contract.

Permanent plot locations with nested circular plots, strip plots and transects for periodic surveys to determine composition (species), abundance (cover or stem density), and size distribution (diameter, height) of vascular plants ranging from forbs to trees. Vegetation data collection occurred pretreatment (1997 or 1998) and post-treatment (2001, 2003 and 2005).

Initially a random selection of 140 plot centers from a 50-m grid of prospective sample points. Plots established in initial survey and maintained unless inordinately disturbed for all subsequent surveys.
Minimal processing to calculate sampling unit totals or averages. Processing performed in spreadsheet environment.

Data field checked for completeness both on site and during post-collection compositing. Data screened for erroneous entries (magnitude) or invalid coding. Repeated observations checked for consistency across years of survey.
Manual keyboard entry to spreadsheet (Excel) of data transposed from hand-written field data collection forms.
Sixteen forest stands within the Lookout Creek and McRae Creek drainages, HJ Andrews Experimental Forest, regenerated after old-growth harvest in the 1950s.

samplingDescription.para: Randomized complete block experiment with 4 treatments and 4 blocks. Treatments consist of repeated harvest entries to maintain stand density between 1) RD 30 and 50 (light thin); 2) RD 20 and 40 (moderate thin); 3) RD 20 and 40 with small 1-tree height gaps (thin with gaps); and unthinned (reference).

attribute.attributeDefinition: Snag Decay Class - Also see related file Decay Class chart

codeDefinition.definition: original color; bark 100% present; branch system is all present; sapwood condition is sound, hard, original color; heartwood condition is sound, hard, original color
faded color; variable bark; no fine branches, few limbs; sapwood condition - decay evident, fibrous, firm to soft; heartwood condition - upper bole has incipient decay and base is sound

faded, gray, light to reddish brown color; variable bark; limb stubs only; sapwood cond: soft, fibrous; heartwood cond: upper bole-advanced decay, base-incipient decay hard to firm; probe passes through sapwood, heartwood meets firm or hard core

reddish to dark brown color; variable bark; few or no stubs; sapwood condition - soft cubicle (may be encased in hardened shell); heartwood condition - base has advanced decay; probe passes easily through both sapwood and heartwood
reddish to dark brown color; bark is less than or equal to 20%; no branch system; sapwood gone; heartwood soft sloughing (may be encased in hardened shell); probe passes through easily
Measurement missing or not a snag

attribute.attributeDefinition: Snag Height - total height of snag from ground (uphill side) to existing top.
Snag Top - classification of snag top condition (Intact or Broken)

codeDefinition.definition: Measurement missing or not a snag

attribute.attributeDefinition: Crown Base Height- vertical height from ground (uphill side) to the base of the live crown; live crown base is determined by the lowest occurrence of live limbs occupying one-third or more of the bole circumference (one-third live whorl) .
Crown Class - tree crown position within the canopy of neighboring trees (Dominant, Co-dominant, Intermediate, or Overtopped)

codeDefinition.definition: Dominant - crown emerges from the general canopy layer and receives direct light from the top and all sides
Co-dominant - crown extends to the top of the general canopy layer and receives direct light from the top and only partial direct or filtered light from the sides
Intermediate - crown extends into lower portion of the general canopy layer and receives mostly filtered light from the top and the sides
Overtopped - crown completely beneath the general canopy
